headline: Hedge Funds Pulled Back From Stocks During Selloff
summary: Hedge funds added to the selling pressure in the market on Wednesday and cut their exposure to stocks by the most in a day since last April.  Morgan Stanley's trading desk told clients in a note that Wednesday was the largest single "degrossing" day since April 9, when the market was still volatile following President Trump's "Liberation Day" tariff announcement.  Relative to the broader market, hedge funds ended January "more underweight software than they've been in more than a decade," according to a Morgan Stanley prime-brokerage report.

headline: Morgan Stanley to Host 17th Annual Go Red Women’s Leadership Event in Collaboration with the American Heart Association
summary: NEW YORK, February 05, 2026--In special recognition of the Go Red for Women® campaign, Morgan Stanley Wealth Management will collaborate with the American Heart Association in Westchester and Fairfield Counties, to host the 17th Annual Go Red Women’s Leadership event on Friday, February 6 at 8:00 a.m. EST at Morgan Stanley’s Purchase, NY offices. The event will also be live streamed.

headline: Looking At The Narrative For Glanbia (ISE:GL9) After Subtle Shifts In Street Targets
summary: The small move in Glanbia’s modelled fair value, from €17.71 to €17.74, reflects how recent research is gently recalibrating expectations rather than rewriting the story. With the discount rate held at 6.05% and revenue growth in the model adjusted from 2.48% to 2.89%, analysts are indicating a slightly stronger top line outlook while keeping their view of risk unchanged. Investors can monitor these kinds of gradual shifts in the Glanbia narrative as new information becomes available. Analyst...

headline: 7 Bank Stocks With Solid—and Growing—Dividends
summary: “One of the things that we like about them is that they’re more resilient, and we haven’t seen excessive credit erosion,” says Matt Quinlan, a manager of the $4.7 billion  fund, citing the overall quality of loan portfolios for these banks.  Betsy Graseck, global head of banks and diversified financial research at  Morgan Stanley  points out that the large-cap U.S. banks have plenty of excess capital.  This allows them to buy back a lot of stock, often more than they allocate for dividends.
